Evaluating The Open Network's Onboarding Thesis
Sunny Shi

a day ago ⋅  20 min read

Key Insights

  • TON’s mission of onboarding 500 million users by 2028 is an ambitious goal. However, given how large Telegram’s addressable user base is relative to the rest of crypto, even 10% of that result would be a successful outcome for now.
  • GameFi has already been a winner for TON’s ecosystem, and early conversion rates from top mini-apps provide some validity to the onboarding thesis.
  • Telegram’s native wallets, payments platform, and mini-apps provide a powerful UI/UX advantage which may lead to TON becoming crypto’s preeminent mobile-first blockchain.
  • The bull case for the adoption thesis is that Telegram and TON become crypto’s next killer app, bringing the massive adoption that Web3 is looking for.

Introduction

Onboarding crypto’s next wave of new entrants is becoming an increasingly relevant initiative. Web3 applications are nowhere close to their Web2 counterparts in user count. Blockchains often feel like an echo chamber, populated mostly by crypto-natives waiting for the rest of retail to move onchain. Investors also need incremental liquidity to sustain asset prices over time, meaning the sought after “supercycle” is unattainable without mass adoption events.

However, given that the barrier to entry for learning crypto’s UI/UX is still too high, we need large and impactful players to remove consistent points of friction that new users often encounter. Over the past year we’ve seen attempts at tackling this problem, with Coinbase building out a fierce effort around Base, and recently, with South Korean Web2 players Kakao and Naver launching Kaia to become Asia’s most adopted blockchain.

Now TON, a Layer-1 blockchain partnered with Telegram, has firmly joined the onboarding race, eyeing Telegram’s 900 million Monthly Active Users (MAUs) as an enticing distribution channel. The TON Foundation outlined an ambitious goal of onboarding ~500 million people to crypto by 2028, a number that is multiple times larger than the current crypto user base in its entirety. While TON says 500 million users only represent 30% of Telegram’s projected MAUs, half a billion is a large number that will solicit skepticism around how they’ll be able to accomplish such a feat, and whether that result is achievable.

This report will briefly explore what TON is, cover the current problems surrounding onboarding, and how TON plans to address them. Finally we’ll evaluate the TON mass adoption thesis by reviewing early results and determine whether 500 million users on TON is a reasonable outcome to expect this decade.

What is TON?

History

TON, or The Open Network, was first devised by the founders of Telegram (the Durov brothers) as a blockchain that could drive the messenger’s in-app economy. Development efforts on the project had to end following a 2020 SEC suit regarding Telegram’s involvement with TON.

Consistent with crypto’s ethos, TON and Telegram’s community subsequently revived open source development efforts through the TON Foundation. A watershed moment arrived in September of 2023 when Telegram announced a planned integration with TON, re-aligning the goal of establishing the blockchain as Telegram’s primary payment rails. This time, TON would be acting as an external partner to avoid another litigation event.

Recent growth efforts have been driven by the TON Foundation who has invested heavily in ecosystem initiatives. Early miners and current validators of TON that recently owned ~85% of TON token supply and are suspected to be related to the TON Foundation, have largely funded these investments. So far the aforementioned holders have been behaving in a way that is aligned with the interests of the Foundation and tokenholder community, and some concessions have been made to freeze idle wallets within this pool of holders. However, the situation does indeed pose a key risk to prospective investors and participants in TON, and its implications are an ongoing discussion within the community. For now, the presence of these holders casts an overhang over the decentralization of governance as well as the stability of the asset.

The Architecture of TON

The TON blockchain is essentially a multi-level, hierarchical blockchain system designed to enhance scalability, speed, and efficiency compared to traditional blockchains. At its core, TON employs a system of "shardchains" and "workchains" that work together to process and validate transactions in parallel. Shardchains are smaller, more manageable chains that handle subsets of the overall transaction load. Multiple shardchains together form a workchain, which can be specialized for different tasks or applications. At the top level, the masterchain oversees the entire network, ensuring coherence and security by recording the state of all workchains and shardchains. There can only be one masterchain.

The key to TON’s scalability is found in its dynamic sharding mechanism and parallel workchain management. Shardchains within each workchain can split and merge according to the transaction loads they manage. When the burden on a shardchain becomes too great, another shardchain can be added within the workchain and the load is redistributed. Likewise, more and more workchains can be created for specific functions to reduce the load on the main workchain, akin to a new Avalanche subnet or a Polkadot parachain. Shardchains and workchains process transactions in parallel and are asynchronous, meaning that they work through their tasks independently. In this way, TON is often referred to as a “blockchain of blockchains”.

For example, when you send tokens from your wallet to another on the TON blockchain, the transaction starts in the shardchain where your wallet resides. Validators in this shardchain validate and include the transaction in a block. If the recipient's wallet is in the same shardchain, the transaction is straightforward. If it is in a different shardchain, the transaction message is passed asynchronously to the recipient's shardchain, where it is again validated and included in a block. State updates from both shardchains are summarized and sent up and through to the masterchain in strict logical order, which finalizes the transaction, ensuring network-wide consistency. This bottom-up approach allows for efficient handling of many transactions simultaneously.

At the moment TON has just one active workchain called the basechain running the TON Virtual Machine. All current TON activity resides there, with transactions processed by the shardchains within the basechain. If the community deems it necessary or desirable, more workchains can be added.

In a performance test of the TON blockchain, the Foundation achieved a TPS of 104,000+, setting a new transaction speed record for a blockchain. However, these results were produced in an idealized test environment. So far the blockchain has managed to process over 8 million transactions a day (~92 TPS) at its peak without any issues, but problems arose during TON’s own inscription craze, when the basechain split into 11 shardchains within a rapid window. Due to intense load on certain validators, select shardchains’ processing speeds dropped to 1 TPS - highlighting that test results are unreliable when stresstesting the blockchain in real conditions. With that being said, TON’s record TPS serves as a proof of concept as the technical community addresses issues like validator hardware requirements over time. Of note, the hierarchical structure of TON creates scalability but adds latency, where TON trails peers like Solana.

TON currently hosts 362 validators. Last November, Animoca Brands announced that they had become the largest validator on the TON network. Also worthwhile to consider is that Whiterabbit’s holder analysis found that 170-182 of the current validator set probably consists of members of the connected early miner cohort discussed earlier. Since these wallets are connected to the TON Foundation, they could be viewed as a voting bloc which promotes (or determines) the Foundation’s goals.

The Problem

Crypto has an onboarding problem. Among the list of bottlenecks preventing adoption is friction on the wallet level. Secret recovery phrases can look complicated when setting up a self-custodied wallet, and the idea of losing assets permanently as the result of forgetting your recovery phrase or misclicking links may feel daunting. We see this issue demonstrated in the outsized interest in owning/trading crypto assets through CEXs and ETFs.

Peer-to-Peer (P2P) crypto transfers are also hard to manage. Even experienced crypto natives still hold their breaths when they send large sums of value from one wallet to another using copy and pasted wallet addresses.

Finally, the majority of crypto applications today rest in web apps and browsers. The consumer technology landscape has largely shifted towards mobile, and this represents a hurdle crypto has to cross for mass consumer adoption. Phantom’s success in the mobile app stores despite unimpressive UI/UX (vs. Web2 applications) is telling of the demand for a mobile crypto solution.

TON’s Proposed Solution

TON is aiming to smooth out the friction for new users by leveraging Telegram’s interface. The Telegram app gives TON key differentiated advantages when it comes to UI / UX.

Largely speaking, the plan is to:

  • Make wallets more accessible by integrating native wallets into Telegram.
  • Use Telegram’s social graph to enable a seamless peer-to-peer (P2P) crypto payments network.
  • Incentivize a thriving mini-app ecosystem that gives Telegram users engaging things to do while also providing a Web2 experience for Web3 applications on mobile.

Wallets

There are several non-custodial wallet options for TON that can be used in browser extension form, but Telegram offers both a custodial and self-custodied wallet natively within Telegram built by third party developers and endorsed by the app. These two wallets have been constructed with user-friendliness in mind.

  • The wallets can be easily found and set up directly in the settings of the Telegram app.
  • Both wallets can be linked to a Telegram account and used natively within the app, allowing users to send money, invest in crypto and interact with Web3 protocols that have a mini-app without ever leaving the messenger.
  • The custodial wallet does not provide private keys but allows users to recover their wallet easily, alleviating any reservations new crypto users might have about writing down a recovery phrase.
  • TON Space, the self-custodied wallet, does provide private keys but is planning to build out an optional recovery mechanism for users who prefer more accessible recovery methods similar to Coinbase’s smart wallet.
  • Crypto can be onboarded with a credit card, providing a frictionless on-ramp method.

Payments

Because wallets can be linked to accounts, Telegram users can access perhaps the easiest to use P2P crypto transfer product in Web3. By leveraging Telegram’s social graph, users can easily send USDT or TON to friends and new connections through human readable Telegram profiles. The result is an experience that is more akin to sending somebody money through Venmo or WeChat than through Metamask or Phantom. The goal is to create an environment where crypto transfers don't feel like crypto transfers.

The innovations provided above unlock a $3 trillion global P2P payments market for TON to tap into. The payment channel can allow for cross-border payments with instant settlement, free from bank network restrictions and added fees.

Mini-Apps

Mini-apps are a crucial component of the TON value proposition. Mini-apps open up directly in Telegram, and provide a smooth landing page for developers to showcase their applications while having access to Telegram’s suite of Bot APIs and integrations. As more and more onchain protocols build out mini-app functionality, TON + Telegram has the capability to provide the best mobile UI/UX in crypto, given the lack of crypto mobile apps out there that can deliver an experience as seamless as Telegram mini-apps. While GameFi / social gaming has been the first and most obvious use case so far, users can currently access Telegram mini-apps of the chain’s largest DEXs, lending protocols, and perp trading platforms. Perp DEX Storm Trade for example, has built its application solely for the Telegram mini-app format.

While web-app warriors in crypto might scoff at the idea of interacting with the blockchain on a mobile device, top Telegram trading bots combine for over $100 million in average daily volume (on par with MetaMask swaps) using the same mobile UI/UX as Telegram mini-apps.

It’ll take more developers to come onboard, but TON could realistically become the first real blockchain that sees more engagement on mobile than on web browsers, opening up a funnel of new retail users who prefer the mobile interface.

To illustrate mobile’s addressable market, despite gaming publisher Activision Blizzard owning some of the most valuable console and PC gaming IP in the industry (e.g. Call of Duty, Overwatch, World of Warcraft), the company generated more annual revenues and registered higher MAUs on Mobile than it did on Console & PC combined. This was driven by widespread distribution and user acquisition (UA) on Candy Crush and their other top mobile titles.

Early Metrics

Let’s review what early onchain metrics say about onboarding progress.

Total Value Locked (TVL)

Several headlines have focused on TON’s rapid rise in TVL as a positive indicator that users have started to migrate.

Although still impressive, most of TON’s TVL gains come from its two largest DEXs STON.fi and DeDust. Much of this has to do with the TON foundation incentivizing pools for USDT, with current TON / USDT APR’s at ~75%. TON / USDT pools on DeDust and STON.fi account for over $500 million in combined TVL, representing the bulk of TON’s total TVL.

These are not crypto novices onboarding from Telegram. Instead, savvy yield-seekers are market making on TON’s DEXs to capitalize on boosted pools, and will most likely move elsewhere when rewards become less attractive.

Daily Active Addresses (DAAs)

DAAs show that TON has passed a major milestone, surpassing Ethereum’s average DAAs in the month of June. Given that TON’s main objective and core narrative is onboarding users to the blockchain, active addresses is probably the most important readily available metric to observe as we assess the early thesis.

While not all of these addresses are likely to represent onboarded Telegram users (a large % may either be bridged over or bots), the timing of the growth pattern coincides with the initiation of The Open League, a Foundation driven initiative to invest roughly $115 million worth of Toncoin into developers and applications that show promising KPIs.

GameFi Metrics are Promising

TON’s first successful onboarding catalyst has been GameFi. Perhaps the best example of this is the tap-to-earn meta kickstarted by TON’s Notcoin project. Notcoin and other mini-apps of this genre typically involve a user constantly tapping their phone to level-up and earn rewards as the base mechanic. More playable features can be layered in and in-game rewards can be turned into NFTs. The games are also highly social, with leaderboards, squads and occasional competitions.

As the first popular tap-to-earn game, Notcoin’s interest quickly spiraled, accumulating over 40 million users. After its TGE, it became TON’s most widely held token. In fact, outside of DOGE, NOT has the highest holder count out of any other active memecoin at ~2.5 million wallets. NOT was also the first TON altcoin to be listed on Binance and OKX. The token is currently trading at a valuation of over $1 billion with 100% of the token supply circulating.

If Notcoin was the predecessor, Hamster Kombat was the evolution of the tap-to-earn genre, taking the format and adding a Hamster themed spin. The game is perhaps TON’s greatest marketing story, now amassing 31.5 million subscribers on YouTube. The official twitter has said that the app has hit 200M users, and if those claims are true, Hamster Kombat has acquired as many new users as top iOS and Android mobile games have in 2023.

Hamster Kombat is pre-TGE. When the token launches in July, it’ll most likely spawn another leading token within TON’s ecosystem. Other tap-to-earn games like Pixelverse have gone through investment rounds with prominent VCs on their cap table.

TON's GameFi utility presents a meaningful penetration driver as it is easily understood by crypto outsiders and brings concentrated attention to a currently stagnant sector of Web3. Some of the same complaints about games looking “low quality” or “too simplistic” that are being lobbied onto current TON gaming apps were also used as criticism for Axie Infinity, crypto’s most successful game. Interestingly enough, Axie was largely adopted by international userbases looking to earn speculative virtual currency, and they’re currently reflecting the same interest in TON’s gaming ecosystem. Additionally, messenger based social games like Farmville and Gamepigeon are inherently prone to virality due to the fact that they are shareable. For reference, the founder of Toncoin has said that 94% of Notcoiners had come from referrals.

When analyzing Telegram’s largest GameFi communities, it’s imperative to parse through what percentage of users and actions are really onchain. Most of the impressive DAU numbers touted by Telegram’s GameFi protocols are actually Web2 derived, usually involving mini-apps that are not capturing onchain transactions. However, the numbers themselves, if true, are undeniably impressive even among Web2’s standards, and each subsequent game brings an opportunity to onboard users with TGEs. Furthermore, all of these projects were able to bootstrap winning communities within the span of a couple of months, speaking to the inherent virality and mindshare of the Telegram network.

Driving Onchain Conversion

Mini-apps need to become “mini-dapps”. As mentioned earlier, The Open League is a foundation driven effort that is accelerating that path by rewarding teams in projects that display strong onchain KPIs. Leaderboards depict the onchain statistics of currently leading projects, and the Season 4 results show promising metrics.

In a 2 week period, top 5 performers on season 4 of The Open League attracted millions of Telegram users and hundreds of thousands of Unique Active Wallets (UAWs) who made the move onchain. SquidTG, a game leveraging inscriptions, has boasted a strong Telegram to onchain conversion rate at ~60%. As The Open League continues, more and more developers will be targeting onchain metrics in order to win rewards, also acting as TON’s best sources of onboarding activity.

Catizen is an emerging north star within TON’s mini-app landscape that is actually registering users onchain. The game has amassed over 1 million onchain addresses and over 14.2 million onchain transactions. The team has included design elements which introduce users to DeFi concepts, promoting long term value to TON.

Evaluating the Onboarding Thesis

To evaluate TON’s thesis of bringing 500 million users onchain, we’ll look at onchain conversion rates for leading Telegram mini-apps. A discussion will be had on what level of onboarding should be quantified as a win for TON, and whether mini-apps could be crypto’s next killer app. Finally we highlight risks to the thesis.

Is 500 million users achievable?

It’s a lofty goal. Looking at early GameFi standouts does give us a clue about the potential for Telegram mini-apps to convert users into TON addresses.

Despite Notcoin’s immense success, player to claims ratio indicates a conversion rate of around 12.5% (around 5 million people claimed post TGE). Catizen had an onchain participation rate of ~7%. Most other Open League participants are yielding conversion rates that are even lower.

Judging by these early case studies, TON's goal of onboarding 30% of Telegram’s MAUs seems a little too ambitious. Especially when considering even fewer converts are actually remaining active and finding other things to do onchain.

So 30% would be an extraordinary outcome based on early data, but how many conversions should the market recognize as an achievement? Rational investors are most likely not underwriting ~500 million TON users, and in their defense, TON does not need to hit close to that result to be able to declare their onboarding efforts a success. In fact, for TON to surpass either Solana’s or Ethereum’s L1s + L2s current monthly active addresses they simply need to convert less than 5% of its reported ~900 million MAUs into monthly users onchain. This is a far more reasonable outcome, and if achieved today, would make TON the most populated chain by monthly active addresses.

So while TON’s goal to onboard 500 million MAUs is perhaps too ambitious, it would require just 10% of that number for TON to justify its narrative. This of course, doesn’t account for any expected growth yet to come from Solana and Ethereum, but Telegram itself is also rapidly adding more total users on an annual basis.

TON’s achievements in less than a year since the official Telegram partnership has proven to be highly encouraging with this in mind.

The bull case for TON and Telegram is that mobile enabled mini-apps develop into crypto’s next killer app, which brings along the massive adoption that TON is looking for. In order for consumer applications in crypto to fully inflect their user growth at a Web2 rate, they need to become social phenomena while looking and feeling like your top of the line Web2 application. Mini-apps bring both qualities to the table.

Notcoin and Hamster Kombat are already a demonstration of what is possible - combining mini-apps’ mobile UI/UX with Telegram’s accessible social platform. Few novel blockchains have had the ability to develop a meta like tap-to-earn this early on in their development cycle. Mini-apps’ true potential is their ability to turn on retail attention at any moment, and because of this, TON’s onboarding results likely won’t be linear. Nobody can predict if / when TON will strike gold again.

Looking forward, there’ll likely be ebbs and flows within TON’s key onchain metrics, but unlike other protocols on crypto, users are probably not going to leave Telegram. A probable scenario would be that momentary catalysts like Notcoin continue to onboard users onchain in waves. TON will need to build out the rest of their consumer Web3 ecosystem in DeFi, NFTs, and memecoins, to encourage those users to stick around.

Risks to the Onboarding Thesis

There are currently some significant hurdles for TON to manage before it becomes a fully fledged L1 that can compete with the likes of Solana and Ethereum.

  • The limitations of FunC, TON’s native programming language, presents a challenge. Developers learning the language have already mentioned that it is not widely known, and takes a bit to get used to. This poses a significant barrier of entry on the supply side of new protocols being created.
  • TON’s current growth is aided by incentives driven by the TON Foundation through USDT pool incentives and The Open League. This raises valid concerns about what happens when the music stops. However, The TON Foundation also has a long runway for spending, given that they were donated $1.5 billion worth of TON from validators in 2022 (TON was trading in the $2 range). The Foundation has continued to earn backers and likely possesses more dry powder to allocate, meaning we may see many more seasons of The Open League to come.
  • Telegram’s native wallets are currently inaccessible to U.S. users. For geofencing to end, the regulatory stance in DC for crypto products would need to soften. Currently, wallets are still being rolled out in phases across different geographies.

Conclusion

TON’s exclusive integration with Telegram brings on a powerful and incentivized ally that yields several capabilities which set the chain apart from other L1s and L2s trying to onboard retail. Perhaps the most impactful is the potential to become crypto’s preeminent mobile-first blockchain driven by Telegram’s native wallets, P2P social payments and mini-apps. Despite lofty goals to onboard 30% of Telegram’s MAUs by 2028, TON could do with a much lower conversion rate of just 5% in the near future to justify its existence within crypto’s top echelon of assets. Finally, early indicators in GameFi are highly encouraging given the new-look TON has had a runway of less than a year.
